@node "Introduction" "What is it for ?"

      @{b}@{i}What is it for ?@{ub}@{ui}

      @{fg highlight}A little story :@{fg text}
      
      One day, I wanted to cleanup my LIBS: directory. But, what libraries
      could I delete ?? So, why not write a program that could help me in this
      hard task.

      Then, this wonderful program lets you :

         - know '@{"resources" link "Getting started" 0}' used by one or more
           executable(s)
         - know programs that use one or more resource(s)
         - know available resources in your computer :-)
@endnode

@node "Getting started" "How does it work ?"

      @{fg highlight}Some definitions@{fg text}

      @{b}@{i}What is a resource?@{ub}@{ui}
                            
      A 'resource' is a file needed by a program to work. It can
      be a library, a font, a device ...
      These files are identified by their extension. ResourceManager uses
      this in order to know resource(s) used by a program. 

      @{b}@{i}What is an executable?@{ub}@{ui}

      An executable is a file that begins with the following bytes :
      000003f3 00000000. It can be a library, a program, a device, ...

      @{"Tutorial" link "Tutorial" 0}

      @{"Interface" link "Interface" 0}
@endnode

@node "Tutorial" "Tutorial"

      You can launch ResourceManager with a cli or with the WorkBench. The
      program displays a window, bouh! it is empty snif!. How full this window.


      @{fg highlight}Looking for programs and used resources :@{fg text}

      Press "Start scanning" and type "SYS:" in the 'requester' then press
      "OK". Your hard drive light flashes and two lists grow up with
      programs' names and resources' names. You can filter the resource type
      with the cycle gadget. The information bar displays the current scanned
      directory.
      Yeah, now it is your turn to work.
      You can get information about programs and resources with the
      @{"information window" link "InfoWindow" 0}.
      You can save the ResourcesManager work with the item "@{"Save ..." link "Interface" 0}"


      @{fg highlight}Looking for available resources :@{fg text}

      ResourcesManager can displays the available resources on your computer.
      Choose the item "@{"Get available resources" link "Get available resources" 0}"in the menu.
      Choose the drive that you want to scan. If you want to see what the
      computer does then press "Available" in the 'register group' "Resources".
      You can filter the resource type with the cycle gadget. You can stop the
      scanning clicking on "Stop scanning".
      Zzz... ResourcesManager is working for you, then you can get information
      about available resources with "@{"Available resource Information" link "AvailRscInfoWindow" 0}". You can
      clean your drive with "@{"Move ..." link "Move selected resources" 0}" or "@{"Delete ..." link "Delete selected resources" 0}".
      Then you can "@{"save" link "Interface" 0}" your work.
@endnode

